bib_record.title: Proton Capture to Excited States of 16O: M1, E1, and Gamow-Teller Transitions and Shell Model Calculations

free_txt: Area of the gamma ray peaks were
extracted by fitting experimentally deduced line
shapes to the spectra. No background subtraction was
necessary for the capture gamma rays. For the
reaction gamma rays an empirical background line
shape determined at bombarding energies below the p12
threshold was used. In fitting the spectra, the
relative separation of observed lines was fixed by
the known energy differences of the final states. The
width of the line shape for the capture gamma rays
was assumed to increase linearly with energy, whereas
for the reaction gamma rays the width was kept
constant.
Authors, of this article, assume that readers are
familiar with their previous results, references #3-6
and reaction Q-value. Consequently, gamma0 stands for
ground-state proton capture, gamma1gamma2 non-ground
state captures (6.05, 6.13 MeV) and gamma3gamma4 non-
ground state captures (6.92, 7.12 MeV). Essentially,
it is about transitions in 16O that involved the
ground, first four excited states and observed
resonances and M1 and E1 resonance strengths.
25x25 cm NaI spectrometer with plastic
scintillator anticoincidence shield.
Polarized proton beams with energy 6.2-9.1
MeV.
Polarized beams were used to measure
excitation functions at Thetagamma=90 degrees for
proton energies between 6.2 and 9.1 MeV. Using the
unpolarized proton beam and 15N enriched melamine
target 90 degrees excitation functions were measured
for incident energies between 2.5 and 6.3 MeV.
Information on the gamma-rays from the alpha1, p12,
and p3 exit channels was obtained by digitizing the
lower energy part of the gamma-spectrum in a second
ADC. This second spectrum was prescaled by a factor
of 10 and did not have the anticoincidence
requirement from the plastic shield surrounding the
NaI.
The data below 7.4 MeV were taken
with 0.3 mg/cm2 N-15 target with Ni entrance (0.6
mg/cm2). At higher energies a thicker N-15 target
and thicker Ni foils
